{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608552"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:32:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16005"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16005"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8696"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114798"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8696"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16005"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96801"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"6739"},{"type":"tags","id":"8666"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20807"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20811"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114798","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114798"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic development, the face forms from several prominences that arise from the pharyngeal arches. These structures are populated by migrating neural crest cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the embryological origin of the mandibular prominence?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Develops from the first pharyngeal arch","Derives from neural tube cells","Arises from the second pharyngeal arch","Originates from the frontonasal prominence","Forms from the maxillary prominence"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edevelopment from the first pharyngeal arch\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. The mandibular prominence arises from the first pharyngeal arch and gives rise to the lower jaw, including Meckel\u0027s cartilage and the muscles of mastication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDerivation from neural tube cells\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the skeletal and connective tissues of the mandibular prominence are formed by cranial neural crest cells, not neural tube cells. \u003Cstrong\u003EArising from the second pharyngeal arch\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as the second arch contributes to the hyoid bone and neck structures. \u003Cstrong\u003EOriginating from the frontonasal prominence\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this structure forms the forehead, nose, and nasal septum. \u003Cstrong\u003EForming from the maxillary prominence\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as while also derived from the first pharyngeal arch, this is a separate prominence that forms the upper jaw and cheeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these developmental relationships helps explain conditions like Pierre Robin sequence, where mandibular development is affected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The mandibular prominence develops from the first pharyngeal arch and forms the lower jaw and associated structures.","Neural crest cells migrate into the first pharyngeal arch to form the skeletal and connective tissues of the mandible.","The mandibular prominence gives rise to Meckel\u0027s cartilage and the muscles of mastication."],"references":["Jaruga A, Ksiazkiewicz J, Kuzniarz K, Tylzanowski P. Orofacial Cleft and Mandibular Prognathism-Human Genetics and Animal Models. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Jan 16;23(2):953. doi: 10.3390/ijms23020953. PMID: 35055138; PMCID: PMC8779325.","Rinkoff S, Adlard RE. Embryology, Craniofacial Growth, And Development. [Updated 2023 Jul 3]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK572156/","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96801"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16005"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96801"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-20T12:05:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-20T12:06:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8696"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114798"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{